DESCRIPTION:Join us for a curator-led guided walk of the exhibition Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany\, and Empire.\n\nBetween the 17th and 20th centuries\, the Indian subcontinent was the site of extensive botanical surveys under colonial rule. Plant collection and classification were closely tied to imperial economic\, medical\, and political interests\, and botanical illustration played a central role in this project. Bringing together a new and historically significant collection of botanical art from this period\, the exhibition draws on recent scholarship to recover the often uncredited identities and histories of the Indian artists who made them.\n\nShrey Maurya\, curator of the exhibition and Research Director at Impart\, leads this guided walk through the layered histories embedded in these artworks\, and their relevance to how we understand the natural world today.\n\n‘Paper Gardens’ marks the continuation of a sustained\, years-long collaboration between MAP and Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.
DTEND:20260308T070000Z
DTSTART:20260308T060000Z
SUMMARY:See like a Curator: Paper Gardens
UID:1205@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/see-like-a-curator-paper-gardens/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Website-cover-images-new-2026-02-25T123857.094.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260303T051913Z
DESCRIPTION:Experience the exhibition through the eyes of a botanical artist.\n\nLed by Bangalore-based\, self-taught artist Nirupa Rao\, this guided walk explores plants not as isolated specimens\, but as dynamic\, living beings embedded within rich ecological worlds. From strangler figs to basket ferns\, Rao’s illustrations in the exhibition reveal trees as thriving micro-ecosystems — alive with birds\, insects\, and other forms of life that shape their survival.\n\nThis programme is in conjunction with the ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art Botany and Empire.\n\n‘Paper Gardens’ marks the continuation of a sustained\, years-long collaboration between MAP and Impart — an online platform fostering greater public engagement with the art and cultural histories of South Asia.
DTEND:20260307T070000Z
DTSTART:20260307T060000Z
SUMMARY:See like an Artist: Paper Gardens
UID:1202@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/see-like-an-artist-paper-gardens/
